Not a draw at all! Look at this: 

<pre>
  . . O .    . . O .    . . O .    . . O .
  X ./. .    X ./X .    X ./X\.    X ./X\.
  .\O X . -&gt; .\O/X . -&gt; .\O/X O -&gt; .\O/X\O
  . X O\.    . X O\.    . X O\.    . X O\X
  . ./. X    . ./. X    . ./. X    . ./. X
  . O . .    . O . .    . O . .    . O . .
</pre>

X wins! You have to remember that bridges (or links) span a
knight's move.<br>
However -- 

<pre>
  O_  .   .   X
    --__     /
  .   X --O / .
     /     /  
  . / O_  X   .
   /    --__  
  X   .   . --O 
</pre>

this is a draw, but increase the size of the board by one more row
of holes on each side, and it isn't. (I luv ASCII !!!). With the
size of the Twixt boards, I think that the only draw comes from
running out pieces (I can't remember what happens when you run out
of pieces, do you recycle them or is it called a draw?) 

